ax. Do not quote or place tool-call markup inside explanatory text; when you decide to call the tool, emit the tool call itself.\nIf you use MOUSE, include integer row and col arguments.\nEFFICIENCY BUDGET \u2014 your score on each level is (baseline_actions / your_actions)^2, so every wasted action costs you quadratically.\nLevel 1: you have used 110 actions; a strong score needs about 39 or fewer. You are 2.8x over the target.\nIf you are not steadily making progress toward the level goal, commit to your single best hypothesis and the shortest sequence that tests it \u2014 do not exhaustively scan rows/columns or enumerate every option. Test one idea, read the result, then decide.", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "Interesting! The 7th UP action was stopped early because it was a \"no_impact_action\". This means the blue bar reached its topmost position after 6 UP moves, and the 7th UP had no effect.\nAlso, I notice the 7th UP changed only 2 cells (the HUD), confirming it was a no-impact move.\nSo the blue bar can move UP by 6 steps from rows 36-39: 36 - 6*4 = 12, so rows 12-15. Wait, but I expected rows 8-11. Let me recalculate.\nFrom rows 36-39, UP x 6 \u2192 rows 36 - 6*4 = 12, so rows 12-15. The 7th UP was no_impact, meaning the blue bar can't go above rows 12-15.\nBut earlier I thought the topmost position was rows 8-11. Let me check the current position.\nActually, looking at the image, the blue bar is now near the top, just below the charcoal/magenta blocks. Let me verify the exact position.\nAlso, I notice the SPACE action was NOT executed because the batch was stopped early after the 7th UP (which was no_impact). So I need to try SPACE separately.\nBut wait, I already tried SPACE many times and it was always no_impact. Let me think about this differently.\nActually, I just realized something important. The UP actions changed 162-163 cells each (except the last one which changed 2 cells). This is consistent with the blu